1/ Do schizophrenic patients request more information than healthy controls? We hypothesize that there is a difference in the amount of information requested between schizophrenic patients and healthy controls. We hypothesize that schizophrenic patients request less information than healthy controls due to deficits in directed exploration and increased aversion to uncertainty.

a- Assumptions check

# Normality test
shapiro.test(mydata$Info_tot[mydata$subCond == 0])

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mydata$Info_tot[mydata$subCond == 0]
W = 0.97573, p-value = 0.6349
shapiro.test(mydata$Info_tot[mydata$subCond == 1])

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mydata$Info_tot[mydata$subCond == 1]
W = 0.95597, p-value = 0.2124
# Bartlett test (variance equality for two groups)
bartlett.test(mydata$Info_tot ~ mydata$subCond, data = mydata)

    Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances

data:  mydata$Info_tot by mydata$subCond
Bartlett's K-squared = 2.1017, df = 1, p-value = 0.1471

Conclusion, the variables meet the assumptions, they are not significantly different from a normal distribution (Shapiro-Wilk test p-value > 0.05), and their variances are equal (Bartlett test p-value > 0.05). We can perform a parametric test. The two samples are independent (the values in one sample (control sample) reveal no information about those of the other sample (schizophrenic sample)).

b- Perform statistical comparison

t.test(Info_tot ~ subCond, data = mydata, var.equal = TRUE)

    Two Sample t-test

data:  Info_tot by subCond
t = -2.7037, df = 64, p-value = 0.008772
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group 0 and group 1 is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.12451294 -0.01869799
sample estimates:
mean in group 0 mean in group 1 
      0.2500000       0.3216055

We can conclude that schizophrenic patients request more information than healthy controls.

2/1. Do schizophrenic patients request more information in the social context than in the non-social context? a- Assumption check

library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)

# Normality test
shapiro.test(mydata$Info_social_tot[mydata$subCond == 1])

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mydata$Info_social_tot[mydata$subCond == 1]
W = 0.96293, p-value = 0.3297
shapiro.test(mydata$Info_nonsocial_tot[mydata$subCond == 1])

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  mydata$Info_nonsocial_tot[mydata$subCond == 1]
W = 0.94695, p-value = 0.118
# Subset data for subCond == 1 (Schizophrenic patient)
subset_data <- mydata %>% filter(subCond == 1)

# Convert from wide to long format
long_data <- subset_data %>%
  select(Info_social_tot, Info_nonsocial_tot) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Info_social_tot, Info_nonsocial_tot),
               names_to = "Condition",
               values_to = "InfoValue")

# Bartlett test 
bartlett.test(InfoValue ~ Condition, data = long_data)

    Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances

data:  InfoValue by Condition
Bartlett's K-squared = 0.86583, df = 1, p-value = 0.3521

Conclusion, the variables meet the assumptions, they are not significantly different from a normal distribution (Shapiro-Wilk test p-value > 0.05), and their variances are equal (Bartlett test p-value > 0.05). We can perform a parametric test. The two samples are paired.

b- Perform statistical comparison

t.test(mydata$Info_social_tot[mydata$subCond == 1], 
       mydata$Info_nonsocial_tot[mydata$subCond == 1], 
       paired = TRUE)

    Paired t-test

alternative hypothesis: true mean difference is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -0.083947739 -0.003806042
sample estimates:
mean difference 
    -0.04387689

We can conclude that schizophrenic patients request more information in the non social condition than in the social condition.

2/3. ANOVA two-factors

library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
library(car)

# Convert from wide to long format
long_data <- mydata %>%
  select(sub, subCond, Info_social_tot, Info_nonsocial_tot) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(Info_social_tot, Info_nonsocial_tot), 
               names_to = "Condition", values_to = "Score")

# Ensure factors
long_data <- long_data %>%
  mutate(subCond = factor(subCond),
         Condition = factor(Condition))

# Check the homogeneity of variances across the different groups defined by your factors
leveneTest(Score ~ Condition*subCond, data = long_data)
Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
       Df F value Pr(>F)

      128               
# Two-way ANOVA
anova_model <- aov(Score ~ subCond * Condition + (1|sub), data = long_data)

Summarizing the mean and STD/SEM for all the group and variables

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

sem <- function(x) {
  sd(x, na.rm = TRUE) / sqrt(sum(!is.na(x)))
}

vars_to_summarize <- c("Engagement_tot", "Engagement_nonsocial_tot", "Engagement_social_tot",
                       "Info_tot", "Info_nonsocial_tot", "Info_social_tot")

Data_summarized <- mydata %>%
  select(all_of(vars_to_summarize), subCond) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = all_of(vars_to_summarize), names_to = "Variable", values_to = "Value")

# Summarize full sample and add sample name to variable
summary_full <- Data_summarized %>%
  group_by(Variable) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    std = sd(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    sem = sem(Value),
    min = min(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    max = max(Value, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(Variable = paste(Variable, "(Full Sample)"))

# Summarize subset subCond == 1 and add sample name to variable
summary_subcond1 <- Data_summarized %>%
  filter(subCond == 1) %>%
  group_by(Variable) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    std = sd(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    sem = sem(Value),
    min = min(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    max = max(Value, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(Variable = paste(Variable, "(Schyzophrenic)"))

# Summarize subset subCond == 0 and add sample name to variable
summary_subcond0 <- Data_summarized %>%
  filter(subCond == 0) %>%
  group_by(Variable) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    std = sd(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    sem = sem(Value),
    min = min(Value, na.rm = TRUE),
    max = max(Value, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  mutate(Variable = paste(Variable, "(Healthy control)"))

# Combine (stack) summaries
summary_combined <- bind_rows(summary_full, summary_subcond1, summary_subcond0) %>%
  arrange(Variable)

print(summary_combined)
